European inflation has slipped into food
Accelerated inflation, registered in the euro area, is primarily due to the steep growth in food prices.
The increase in prices in November was higher than expected in the 13 euro area countries, recording - after 2.6 per cent of October - annual inflation of 3.1 per cent - announced the Union Statistical Office based in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts only gave as likely 3 percent - announced the Bloomberg.
The European Central Bank (ECB), unlike the US, British and Canadian issuing banks, did not cut the basic interest, on the grounds that the decrease, along with the rising prices of raw materials and the reduction of forced unemployment, would lead to a spiral of inflation.
The ECB wants to keep the inflation rate below, but at least about two percent.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in the 22th "must negotiate" trap on inflation so that it does not subsequently have to intervene on this issue.
Inflation of 3.3 per cent, recorded in Germany, struck the record for 12 years; while in Spain it increased from 3.6 to 4.1 per cent.
Inflation was fired in the euro area as a result of food and energy prices.
Quotas at the end of wheat increased by 88 per cent and soybean prices reached their highest level since 1973.
Similarly, much more had to be paid in 2007 for vegetable oil and milk products.
The price of crude oil on the world market increased this year by 52 percent, reaching almost $100 per barrel last month.
According to the ECB, inflation in 2008 will rise from 2.1 percent current to 2.5 percent, but by 2009 it will fall to 1.9.
According to analysts, annual inflation will be maintained in the next 3 or 4 months around 3 percent, however the average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, the ECB is expected to reduce interest rates twice during 2008.
