The most expensive is the Auchan, the Tesco has quintupled its prices
The average price increase of 16 per cent remained the hypermarkets of the Budaörs commercial gold triangle, with the difference that VAT had not been increased this year.
Article by Napi Gazdasag
This year also increased by an average of 16 percent in the commercial gold triangle of Budaörs the usual Christmas basket of the newspaper Napi, but in all hypermarkets there was a much higher growth than the thousand HUF.
As in December last year prices in food supermarkets had already been "disappeared", so there was no dramatic percentage increase compared to the high starting point.
However, it is obviously frightening for consumers that what they were able to buy last year at a price far below the nine thousand HUFs, today they can't even do it for ten thousand.
The Napi basket in the hypermarkets studied exceeded the psychological limit of ten thousand HUF with a minimum of 91 HUF.
And the highest value basket was 10573 HUF.
(in 2003 that basket cost 6800 HUF.)
The price of Unicum liquor and fish remained almost at the level of the previous year, but there was a strong increase in turkey breast fillet, walnut and poppy seed.
The price of wheat flour and bread followed the data of the Central Statistical Office, although in the Auchan we also found a kilo of bread for the price of 139 HUF.
The competition did not reduce the price of the product to less than 200 HUF.
It was also surprising in this shop that the price of the Coca-Cola with a redeemable bottle of two liters cost less than 200 HUF, so that this product, even at the price of the bottle, cost only 257 HUF.
However, in the basket of Napi Auchan was the most expensive, while Cora was the cheapest.
According to our calculations, regarding last year's Christmas prices, Cora increased by 15, while Tesco and Auchan with about 18 percent the prices in the Napi basket.
Comparing the most expensive basket values of last year with the cheapest basket of this year, the difference has been 12 percent, while the growth between the cheapest of last year and the most expensive of this year has been 21 percent.
The average growth was 1480 HUF.
Last year the average price growth was 1206 HUF, so during last year's Christmas in prices the increase in VAT was felt.
It was precisely this process that destroyed trade, the supermarkets were visibly unable to decide on the price margin to be applied for each product and to calculate the effect of price change on consumption.
(If the trader misplans the speed of the circulation of a product, it may lose an important benefit in the margin that fits the volume of sales.)
The increase in the price of the Napi basket reached such extremes as a result of the increase in VAT, which the most expensive was higher by 1720 HUF than the value recorded in 2006, while in the cheapest the difference was only an 844 HUF.
This year did not produce such extremes, since the price now highest has been 1630 HUF more than last year and the cheapest also increased by 1284 HUF.
Comparing the two Christmas seasons, there was a catastrophic growth in prices in less than 20 months, in hypermarkets more than 30 percent of the price of essential consumer goods increased.
(However, this does not necessarily confirm the figures of the Central Bureau of Statistics: this office, in the case of some essential foods, recorded a price increase of over 30 per cent in the 12-month period.
For example, in addition to wheat, also in the case of egg.)
According to the Napi basket, in this latter case this seems almost impossible, because in the price of this product which was quite expensive already last year compared to the base, it was recorded, in the worst of cases just 10 percent price increase.
