According to our experiences, most consumers in the three shops visited are no longer interested in prices.
Of all products, large quantities are purchased, while preserved foods are taken from pallets.
In the morning of Wednesday, large queues were formed in the three stores in front of the boxes because the number of customers suddenly increased.
However, we have information that inside the country sales volumes are lower, many multinationals complain to survey institutes because income remains below their plans and not only in the case of food, but also in the case of household appliances.
In many hospitals it is saved with disinfectants
This year, several thousand infections have been registered in hospitals primarily due to the misuse of antibiotics.
The hygiene conditions prevailing in hospitals, bed overcrowding and staff overload do not favor the control of infections - says the head doctor of the department of the National Centre for Epidemiology.
In many hospitals, even disinfectants are saved.
A MRSA infection has recently been diagnosed in the trauma department of the János Hospital.
In a man hospitalized after a serious accident, the presence of antibiotic-resistant bacteria was detected.
The patient was isolated.
The same type of infection occurred in this same hospital early in the year.
A victim of a serious car accident was discharged from the hospital and the same patient was soon returned to the hospital as a result of MRSA infection and has since been unable to perform an important surgical intervention due to the presence of the bacteria in his body.
Until December 10th of this year there have been registered in the National System Nosocomialis Surveillance 1094 cases of hospital infection produced by multi-resistant agents - said Karolina Böröcz, the head doctor of the department of the National Center for Epidemiology.
This means that this number of infections produced by multi-resistant agents has certainly been recorded in hospitals, but no information is available.
Nearly two thirds of the infections (683 cases) are due to MRSA, namely Staphylococcus aureus, which is resistant to methicillin-oxaciline.
One third of humans carry in their nose the bacteria of Staphylococcus aureus (SA) without causing any disease.
Infections produced by the SA (e. g.: inflammation of the throat, tonsillitis, cutaneous infections, wound infections) react well to antibiotics and are easy to treat.
However, once it is applied excessively or improperly to antibiotics, bacteria that normally react well to antibiotics become very resistant bacteria to antibiotics and quickly infect into inadequate hospital conditions.
They can cause severe hospital infections, such as wound infections or septicemia first of all to patients with transient or chronic immunodeficiency, to patients with the weakened organism, to the elderly or to people with low weight.
In the opinion of the doctor-director of the János Hospital there is nothing special about MRSA infection, these infections are daily in hospitals.
The infection should not be confused with the epidemic, the MRSA is only absent - said Tibor Nyulasi - where its presence is not examined.
Antibiotic Resistant
"These patients are isolated, nursing staff attends them in rubber gloves and masks and there are antibiotics suitable for their treatment," said Tibor Nyulasi.
Hospitalised patients are previously examined to verify the presence of MRSA in their body, but it is not even possible to avoid infection in all cases.
It's not fashionable to take samples
It would be possible to prevent MRSA's hospital infections in most cases, but current national hospital circumstances do not favour the prevention of formation and infection with multi-resistant pathogens - says Karolina Böröcz.
Since this infection occurs primarily in hospitals and elderly homes, hospitals should examine hospitalized patients and immediately isolate the patients who carry MRSA into their body.
However, taking microbiological samples is not fashionable in Hungarian hospitals.
This fact is also due to the fact that the National Health Fund does not finance these medical examinations.
So most cases go out to the public when MRSA infections are already visible in the patient - said the head doctor of the epidemiologic center department.
The European Union makes strict commitments for the application of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also national directives to treat infections and pathological tables.
Antibiotic therapy should be addressed, i.e. microbiological tests should be performed to prevent resistance to drugs from occurring, but hospitals do not always meet this requirement.
Microbiological samples are even less frequent in the case of travelling patients or in primary care - Karolina Böröcz said.
Save with disinfectants
Scientific experiments have shown that in most cases MRSA is infected from one patient to another through healthcare personnel.
Therefore, handwashing, the use of rubber gloves and masks is a very important role, but there are also considerable shortcomings in hospitals.
MRSA is infected by drip transmission and direct contact between people, but in national hospital circumstances it is not always possible to isolate the infected patient.
Furthermore, hospital rooms are often crowded, beds are often very close together, although in order to prevent the epidemic, patients should be separated by at least 1.5 metres away.
Unfortunately one can also experience - Karolina Böröcz added - that in economically less favourable hospitals it is saved with disinfectants, there are few nurses and many patients and therefore there is a greater probability for infection.
In the opinion of Karolina Böröcz, where appropriate preventive measures are carried out, fewer such infections are recorded or the infection of the pathogen can be stopped.
Government programme against MRSA
Treatment of MRSA infection is a huge expense for the National Sickness Insurance Fund, so in all countries it is fought against it.
In England, for example, there is a government programme to prevent and reduce MRSA cases.
According to the data provided, MRSA infections appear to have a declining trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) has among its priorities the prevention of multi-resistant agents (including MRSA) and hospital infections due to these pathogens.
