EUR 400 million more for infrastructure
The Hungarian Finance Minister János Veres and the Vice-President of the European Investment Bank (EIB) Marta Gajecka signed three credit limit agreements in Budapest on Friday for a total of EUR 400 million to finance education, transport and the environment infrastructure as well as the energy sector.
The European Investment Bank (EIB) approved in 2006 a budget of EUR 300 million to finance in the Hungarian budget transport and environmental protection projects, which will be made from the grant of cohesion funds, of which the parties had already signed a credit agreement worth EUR 100 million, the contract they have just signed concerns the use of the remaining EUR 200 million.
The EUR 150 million credit contract is also intended to finance the budget of educational projects.
The EIB approved a total of EUR 300 million for this objective in Hungary, on the use of the remaining EUR 150 million, the decision will be taken later by extending the credit contract.
The parties signed a contract for EUR 50 million for innovations, which the budget will mainly use for the innovation and research project at Debrecen University.
During the talks they also covered the theme of the construction of the 4th line of the Metro.
It was agreed that by the time Hungary completes with the EU the details of the Metro funding, they will again deal with the issue whether or not the original contract needs to be modified and how to do so.
According to János Veres, this will take place earlier in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990 the EIB has financed a total of 113 projects in Hungary worth EUR 8.4 billion.
The interest of the appropriations is in line with EURIBOR and the EIB offers a grace period of 8 years, without charge for keeping the credit available to the debtor.
