Fodor and the six percent Hungarian
The Minister of Environment and Hydrology Gábor Foundor reported that meetings at expert level will end on Tuesday and Wednesday after the official inauguration will continue negotiations at ministers' level on the international climate regime after 2012.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries around the world are deliberating on the Bali Roadmap, which provides for post-emission reduction efforts, as set out in the Kyoto Protocol, up to 2012.
Discussions on the particulars between developing and industrialized countries are currently under way.
The United States has already indicated that it does not want to negotiate on precise figures for the moment, although it tends to reach the agreement that compared to the 1990 situation until 2020 it decreases by 25 to 40 per cent the emission of greenhouse gases.
Another major theme of the conference is whether industrialized countries, in addition to reducing emissions, are willing to offer material and technological assistance to countries in need.
An agreement was also reached on aid to developing countries.
The support fund, provided for in the Kyoto Protocol, will be led by a steering board composed of 16 members, probably within the UN Global Environment Fund (GEF) - writes the "Piac é Profit".
The six percent of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, the Minister of Environment and Hydrology Gábor Foundor supports the EU's efforts to maintain its leading role in global climate protection and to promote the signing of the new international agreement by 2009.
The Minister stated that the EU is committed to reducing its greenhouse gas emissions by 20 per cent by 2020, regardless of whether or not the "after-2012 agreement" will be signed and is willing to commit itself to a reduction of up to 30 per cent if the other major developed regions of the world and developing countries are also willing to make commitments in accordance with their responsibility and capabilities.
Gábor Fodor noted that the signatory countries of the 1997 Kyoto Protocol pledged to decrease by 5.2 per cent, within which 15 EU Member States committed to achieving 8 per cent decrease.
Hungary's commitment is to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6 per cent in respect of the period between 1985 and 87, which our country will implement - notes the press release by the Ministry of Environment.
This is much at stake in Bali, since within two years the international agreement on long-term climate policy will have to be signed, because otherwise it is certain that its entry into force will be postponed until after 2012. In this case, the reduction commitments under the Kyoto Protocol will not be immediately followed by a new international emission reduction system, the need of which was warned in its most recent report by the IPCC, the UN international scientific association dealing with climate change, which won the Nobel Peace Prize.
With this, the reduction of emissions would be delayed and an increase of more than 2°C of the Earth's average temperature could not be prevented, because according to scientists it would have immeasurable and irreversible consequences.
British army recruits on YouTube
British army units in a video distributor publish recordings of actions filmed in Iraq and Afghanistan to popularize themselves.
First the British Air Force (RAD) was the one that took advantage of YouTube services: special units displaced in Afghanistan since March 2006 are loading videos about their actions against the Taliban - the BBC reported.
These recordings made with mini cameras mounted on the helmets are controlled in the general Kandahar operations body, then sent to London to be uploaded to the Internet.
The political message is inevitable
There are already 139 recordings from the air force soldiers who have been loaded this way to the Internet and their "channel" has already been seen by more than 75,000 people.
The British Ministry of Defence was registered in spring 2007 under the name "defence headsquaters" and publishes videos of both actions in Iraq and Afghanistan, while both the Ministry of the British Community (Commonwealth Office) and the multinational forces in Iraq (MNFI) have their own YouTube channel.
Operation in Afghanistan
The air force had originally uploaded the videos with recruitment objectives, but in the view of the Ministry of Defence they also serve to present to the public the true objective of the British army's presence abroad.
This kind of propaganda hardly costs anything compared to conventional recruitment television spots - the BBC was declared by the defense expert Gordon Mackenzie - but they inevitably have some political message, since in a specific way they justify the reason for the military actions decided by the government.
The Americans set up a video game
The army is also concerned about the fact that, in addition to the suspiciously edited and censored recordings, amateur videos appear in the distributor, for example, about the death of soldiers: in the "official" propaganda films, a little hypocritical, the officers speak at most of losses, although they do not present the bloody part of the fighting.
In addition, numerous videos recorded in real operations have already been uploaded to the Internet from the battlefields of Iraq and Afghanistan, but the British army is only recently taking advantage of this opportunity.
Americans use a slightly different form for recruitment with video game shooting, downloadable for free, called America's Army, in which in the midst of a more or less real situation the player can put himself directly instead of the soldiers.
