The forces of the giant strike are gathering
The League Unions and the National Federation of Labour Commissions will constitute a strike commission on Friday to coordinate the strike on Monday that will last indefinitely.
On Saturday a protest rally will be held, while on Monday - the day on which the final vote on the public health law will be held - the unemployment rate will begin.
This action will certainly cause great difficulties in transport, as rail traffic will be stopped completely and workers of the Collective Transport Company in Budapest will also be on strike by 13 hours.
In the afternoon of Friday, the League Unions will report on the details of their Monday strike that will be held jointly with the National Federation of Labour Commissions.
The strike commission of the Liga and the National Trade Union of Engineers will also be set up to coordinate the actions of Monday.
On Saturday a protest rally will be held, while on Monday the participating unions will be pronounced on strike indefinitely, if no agreement is reached with the government.
This means that, on the day of the parliamentary vote on the public health law, they did not report on the date of the end of the strike initiated.
If the National Assembly approves the public health law, trade unions will immediately withdraw their call for strike.
On the other hand, if the law is passed, the strike committees will meet and decide on the future.
On the basis of the agenda of Monday of the National Assembly, it is also possible to vote only on the public health law at very late hours of the night, or at best near midnight.
As a result of the strike to be launched on Monday, significant transport difficulties will have to be encountered: in railways there will be no time to work indefinitely, in the morning some of the collective transport of Budapest may be stopped and more than half of the inter-urban bus transport of the Volan companies.
At the same time, at many points in the country, half of the roads will be closed.
Numerous trade unions and civil organizations have joined the strike, their names are constantly updated on the League's website.
Some unions announced their strike indefinitely, others for definite time.
Until Thursday evening the State Railway and the Free Trade Union of Railway Workers (SLTF) were unable to reach an agreement even on minimum services, although, as Christmas parties approached, more and more people were traveling on the trains.
According to information received so far, from the beginning of the day until 1 p.m. workers of the Collective Transport Company in Budapest will be on strike, Budapest airports from 7 to 9 a.m. will hold a four-hour strike the Liga Trade Unions of Electrical Industry and Thermal Energy, the Education Unions called for a 2 a.m. strike and the Democratic Union of Educators from 2 to 8 hours.
The Hungarian Association of Physicians will take a national strike at alternative times and the Democratic Union of Workers of the Health and Social Sector (SDTSSS) which is part of the Trade Union Cooperation Forum will hold a two-hour warning strike.
The most important of the four demands made by the League is that the government withdraw its proposal on public health reform and submit a new conception to a social debate.
The second demand is to gradually introduce the new form of pension calculation which will enter into force next year.
The third is to ensure, even before 2010, that in the case of advance pensions, the possibility that occupations that deserve it may enter the system.
The fourth reason for the strike is that the Free Trade Union of Railway Workers (SLTF) which is part of the League Unions, do not accept the proposal of the Ministry of Economy and Transport on the railway side lines and expect another different proposal.
Political Capital[b1]: In the country there is increased risk by the Hungarian Guard
According to the Risk Analysis Division (Risk Analysing Division) of the Political Capital, the activity of the Hungarian Guard, constituted in August this year with the support of the Movement by a Better Hungary, has from various points of view increased the political risk of Hungary and the region.
In the company's "risk warning" it is written: in relation to the activity of the Hungarian Guard the highest political risk is that "with the worsening of the ethnic tensions between the Roma and non-Gypsy population in Hungary, even in the short term violent ethnic clashes may occur".
The main reason for this is that the political strategy of the Hungarian Guard is probably the provocation of such an event - added the representative of the research institute.
They stated that this was due to one of the main shortcomings of Hungarian political life: "the protagonists of public life gave public debate about the Roma problem to representatives of radical and extremist political groups, who were able to base their political strategy on existing discrepancies between Roma and Hungarians."
This exacerbates the problem, makes normal dialogue impossible, strengthens extremists and increases the likelihood of the outbreak of violent conflicts - they believe.
In addition, according to the Institute of Research, the National Guard's activity, as a result of the great attention of the national and international media, "has significantly deteriorated Hungary's image abroad, especially in terms of the country's stability and democratic development."
They remind us that since the fall of 2006 there has been increasing publicity and momentum for the reorganization of the radical and far-right groups of Hungary and that since the summer of 2007, many organizations have been established in the country that have self-definition of "national self-defense associations".
"The common feature of these groupings is that they are self-defining themselves as civil organizations, while openly proclaiming the training of their members for defence - even armed - (civil defence, national defence, defence of public order), alluding to the ineptitudes of the police, the army, that is, the state" - they add.
