We also celebrate the New Year: both the last day of the old year, and the first day of the new year is festive - the latter especially so that they can rest those who have spent celebrating the old year.
Throughout the year we have eleven parties written with red numbers on the calendar.
It is a national festival on March 15 in memory of the revolution of 1848 and October 23rd, commemorative day of the revolution of 1956.
On 20 August we celebrate the foundation of the State, on 1 May the festival of work, on 1 and 2 November we remind our family and friends who died.
In addition, in our country are two-day parties the Easter of Resurrection, Pentecost and Christmas.
According to the calendar, our state, national or religious parties rarely coincide with a weekend, so it is often made bridge when before or after the party there is only one working day.
In exchange for the extended weekends so, during the previous Saturdays you cannot leave work or school.
It is the Minister of Labour who regulates in his specific decree when it is necessary to work exactly in exchange for the day directly preceding or after the feast.
This legal rule is mandatory for all employers and their employees, as well as for employees and public officials.
However, it is not mandatory for service companies and institutions that, due to their role, work continuously even during holidays.
