A heavy memory
After more than 60 years of confidentiality, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which describe the destinations of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are in free access.
The 47 million file documents, stored over 27 km of shelves at Bad Arolsen (Hesse), were not so far available only for a "humanitarian" purpose, that is, individually and nominally, at the request of an old victim or his rights.
The eleven managing States - such as Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May 2006 to open them to the searchers and historians.
Since the process of ratification of this agreement by all States has been completed, openness has been effective since yesterday.
Sensitive Information
The access of historians to Bad Arolsen will allow for searches " particularly on the displacement of prisoners, the population of the camps and the health status of forced workers ", explains Reto Meistern, the director of these archives administered by the International Commission of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, a number of States, such as Germany, were opposed to the opening up of these nominal documents to the public because of the sensitive nature of certain information.
As well as the supposed homosexuality or mental illness of certain victims of deportation.
The records of the concentration camps or arrest orders established by the Gestapo had been collected after the war for a practical purpose: to find the deported or subjected to compulsory labour and, if necessary, to provide proof of their internment, in order to open the way to their compensation.
Still today in Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent employees deal with tens of thousands of individual requests.
However, access to Bad Arolsen is of limited interest to a part of the scientific community.
" There is nothing fundamentally new to expect from these documents," Professor Wolfgang Benz, director of the Anti-Semitism Research Centre at the University Technische Universität in Berlin, declared in 2006.
