Venus: twin brother of the Earth.
Despite its atmosphere is not suitable for life, Venus is the most Earth-like planet, something that had not been raised so far. The European probe "Venus Express" discovered rays in the atmosphere and whirlwinds in the poles, the same ones that also appear in winter on Earth.
For three decades now, researchers had suspected that there could be rays in Venus.
But now the European probe has brought new evidence: it discovered electromagnetic waves on the edge of the atmosphere. In Venus the rays run from a height of 54 kilometers from one cloud and behind another, tells Cris Russell of the University of California in Los Angeles to the scientific magazine "Nature".
According to the famous model of the origin of Urey-Miller's life, rays caused life on Earth: storms could have caused reactions in the ocean that, for their part, had given rise to amino acids that are the basic components of life.
In Venus it is not so: if ever there was to be life there, that would have to be in one of the first states of evolution," explains Sean Solomon of the Washington Carnegie Institution.
Today, on the surface of Venus there can be no life: atmospheric pressure is almost 100 times higher than on Earth and on the surface reinstate temperatures of 500°C, swaying in such a way that temperatures can be reached below zero.
"Perhaps Venus is a "diabolic" twin of the Earth, but it remains a twin," said Russell.
The main objective of the mission "Venus Express" is to answer the question why Venus, so similar to Earth by its mass and size, has had such a different evolution.
Since the 1990s there were no special missions, just for research on this planet, the launch of "Venus-Express" in November 2005 was a very important step for Venus' research.
The latest results of the research to be presented in many articles of "Nature", according to the researchers' opinion, stress not only the uniqueness of Venus in the Solar System.
"This also demonstrates that neighbouring planets have more common characteristics with the Earth than we had imagined," ESA reports.
Despite the already known stormy winds in the North Pole, researchers discovered in the South Polar region also a vortex formed by the clouds that rotates faster.
This phenomenon reminds the wind flows in the high earthly atmospheric layers of the poles, as described by a team of researchers from Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Institute of Special Astrophysics and Space Physics.
The second planet of the Solar System has the mass almost equal to the Earth and with its equatorial diameter of 12,000 kilometers is almost as large.
This planet also called sunrise star or evening star orbits around the Sun almost 225 days.
But its rotation period is slower: one day in Venus amounts to 243 days on Earth.
Although Venus with its surface temperatures of 460 degrees and with its atmospheric pressure of 92 bars is not much like Earth, scientists start from the basis that both planets had formed under the same conditions.
On the two planets there had been a swarm of water that remained on Earth in the oceans, but in Venus it dissociated into the universe.
While carbon dioxide had become carbon stones on Earth, Venus forms most of the atmosphere.
