Those who relate the terms Sweden and wooden box, think of Ikea, but don't think of Andy Warhol.
Or is it?
Currently the wooden boxes produced in Sweden are like the shadow that weighs on Warhol's list of works.
Most of the ninety-four "type"-bright-box on this list are fake.
After a few months ago the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" questioned the authenticity of Brillo-Boxes of 1968 by Andy Warhol, the Modern Museum Museet in Stockholm conducted internal investigations and reached disappointing conclusions: the six "Brillo-Boxes", which the former director of the museum Pontus Hultén gave to the Museum Moderna Museet, are false, and almost one hundred of the others of "Stock type", which are in circulation in the international art market, also result.
Prehistory is too complicated with a confusing relationship between artistic and sponsored productions.
In 1964 Warhol created in New York his first "Brillo-Boxes", painted the red, blue and white wooden boxes, with the same sample as they had "Brillo" soap powder cards.
According to Warhol, at the exhibition of his 1968 works at the Modern Museum Museet were exposed hundreds of cardboard boxes-bright. These did not make them Warhol (because of the expenses), but they were brought directly from the "Brillo" cardboard factory.
These were not works of art, but copies (which were only some objects) exhibited.
In the same year, 1968, Warhol made it possible to produce in Sweden a wooden box-bright, but were not exposed at the Modern Museet museum.
Witnesses of those times now speak of nearly fifteen boxes, which at that time entered the history of art and auction as originals of the "Brillo-Boxes" of the Stockholm type authorized by Andy Warhol.
In auctions some of them were purchased for more than $100,000.
The problem is that after the famous director of the Pontus Hultén museum made false statements that in 1968 in Sweden were produced and exposed almost a hundred of the wooden boxes that Warhol left to him.
But actually, 105 boxes were produced in the same year 1990 in Malmö for Hulten and for the exhibition in St. Petersburg.
By this time Warhol had already died three years ago.
Lars Byström, the head of the conservatives of the Museum Moderna Museet, investigated six Brillo-Boxes owned the museum and also three of the Swedish private property that were manufactured in 1968 in Stockholm. First they printed and crushed their tight silvers and then painted them in oil with brush.
On the contrary, the structure of the 1990s copies shows that the painting was applied with a roll without printing directly the tight silver. Moreover, it is not the oil painting, but the acrylic painting.
"These boxes have not been authorized by the artist and must be removed from the official list of Brillo-Boxes by Andy Warhol," says Lars Nittve, director of the Museum Moderna Museet and adds that if the Authentication Commission "Andy Warhol Art" in New York will not come to any conclusion, the Moderna Museet museum will classify these six boxes as the copies/objects of exhibition."
Already in Julio The Authentication Commission formally announced that it accepts these "serious accusations" in which these are soap powder boxes.
But from that moment on everything remained in absolute silence.
